      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Knowledge Gap</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Carolyn Segal letter on Clyde Haberman's Oct 9 column about Gov George Pataki's ignorance of E B White</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Highfalutin but Hardly Proud of It,'' by Clyde Haberman (NYC column, Oct. 9):</p>
        <p>I would like to invite Gov. George E. Pataki to attend my class, ''Literature of the City,'' which I teach at Cedar Crest College, in Allentown, Pa. As any one of my students could tell the governor, E. B. White not only wrote ''Charlotte's Web,'' but he is also the author of a classic essay called ''Here Is New York.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Highfalutin but Hardly Proud of It,'' by Clyde Haberman (NYC column, Oct. 9):</p>
        <p>I would like to invite Gov. George E. Pataki to attend my class, ''Literature of the City,'' which I teach at Cedar Crest College, in Allentown, Pa. As any one of my students could tell the governor, E. B. White not only wrote ''Charlotte's Web,'' but he is also the author of a classic essay called ''Here Is New York.''</p>
        <p>There is no dishonor in saying, ''I don't know''; there is great dishonor in saying ''I don't care to know'' and insulting those who do. What sort of standard for education is set by such arrogant ignorance?</p>
        <p>CAROLYN SEGAL  Bethlehem, Pa., Oct. 10, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
